photos.description: Jean (Rothenhoefer) Culver holds Ken Culver, 11.5 months old, in front of the "square grand" piano which allegedly came from the Phillipines where Louis Rothenhoefer was a mining engineeer.

Ken Culver with a 25lb Ling cod, caught from the float at Pt. Lawrence Lodge.  The fish and I were about the same length.  I was using a little metal rod about 4 feet long which crumpled, never to be used again, but I got the fish in with help from someone who gaffed it for me.  This photo made the Seattle Times  - not sure who or why that happened.  {Ken)

Ken and Bruce at the Doe Bay Store and Post Office.  That is the old 1941 Ford "woody" that was famous for leaking exhaust through the back door and causing at least Ken to be car sick unless he stuck his head out the window.  (Ken)
photos.notes: The Doe Bay Store was the center of activity for several reasons.  It had a well stocked store, a post office, sold gas, and was adjacent to the Doe Bay Community Dock where the Mailboat Osage stopped daily.  The store was in front and in the back overlooking Doe Bay was a pub with tables and booths lined around the outside edge.  In my lifetime this never operated, instead serving as a place for local kids to shoot baskets when the weather was inclement.  In the "off season" there were often square dances and a potluck - the kids tore around until they got tired and then slept in their parents cars until the party was over.

photos.location: Back yard Rothenhoefer home in Seattle
photos.description: Not sure of the occasion. The house behind was owned by Mrs. Devin, a sweet grandmotherly woman who welcomed the Culver kids into her home to play with toys that her children had. She would walk me down to the water by the Seattle Yacht Club to feed the ducks. One of my fondest memories of visiting Seattle as a child. (Ken)

photos.people: Ken Culver, age 17 (just barely as my birthday was  August 22.  I graduated from Garfield High School that year and immediately headed for Pt. Lawrence to spend the summer before starting school at the University of Washington.
photos.description: TBD
Just hanging out on the beach.  Notice my brown arms and sun bleached hair. We did not know about sunscreen then.

Ken standing on the stump of a recently fallen very large fir threatening Cabin 2.  Remnants of the decaying stump may still be found covered with brush.  This tree was fallen with a two man hand saw - before the days of gas powered chain saws;
Standing on the first float which connected to the lower platform and the lodge platform.  If you look closely you can see the fish scales just peeking out from behind my right elbow.  (Ken)

Ken with John Holen, the son of one of the Holen Twins that came each year to catch herring.  Good Norwegians - they caught salmon and cod, but the real reason they came for 2 weeks each year was to jig herring!  They smoked them, canned them, and had them for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.  (Ken)
